                           <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td bgcolor="#000000" height="8" width="100%" colspan="3"><span class="header">Dilemma Combos 102</span></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor="#333399" height="2" width="41%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="1%"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td><td height="2" width="58%" bgcolor="#FF9C00"><img src="/stccg/global/images/trek/glear.gif" width="1" height="5"></td></tr></table><TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN=2><SPAN CLASS="header">Rating </SPAN><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/rating/8.gif" BORDER=0></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=9"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=9"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=1680">Matt "Figrin" Kirk</A></FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Description</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%"><span class=text>Second in the series, this article continues examining ways to increase effectiveness of dilemmas in combination. Defensive usage of dilemma combos is stressed in this installment.</span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Article</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%" ><span class=text>In this installment, we&#146;ll examine...<br>
<br>
DEFENSIVE COMBOS<br>
<br>
This category covers the more conventional usage of dilemmas; that is, using filter-killer-wall or wall-killer-filter. Still confused? Let&#146;s take a look at what these shorthand terms mean.<br>
<br>
Filters<br>
These dilemmas do not kill targets; rather, they exclude or separate the target from the rest of the attempting crew/Away Team (AT). Filters rarely have conditions (classification, skill, or other requirements to avoid the ill effects of the dilemma). Examples include Love Interests, Hippocratic Oath, Make Us Go, Chula: the Chandra, and Lineup, among others.<br>
<br>
Killers<br>
These dilemmas simply kill their targets. The best example of a plain and simple killer dilemma is Armus-Skin of Evil. &quot;Kills one personnel in AT (random selection). Discard dilemma.&quot; Sometimes, killer dilemmas will have conditions. Other examples include Microvirus, Denevan Neural Parasites, Dal&#146;Rok, and Borg Ship.<br>
<br>
Walls<br>
These dilemmas usually have difficult conditions, but little or no ill effects for failure to meet the conditions, apart from your crew/AT being &quot;stopped&quot;. Examples include Shaka, When the Walls Fell, Maglock, Emergency Conversion, Primitive Culture, and Founder Secret.<br>
<br>
Most dilemmas fall largely into one of these three categories, but may have characteristics of another. For instance, Berserk Changeling has fairly difficult conditions (3 SEC, 2 hand weapons, Mora Pol, or Interphase Generator), and as a result of failure, it kills one random personnel. In addition, it is a planet/space dilemma. It falls squarely between wall and killer. These qualities have given many players incentive to include it in their decks. <br>
<br>
But what to do with these filters, killers, and walls? The debate has raged on, from top players to local cronies. Many players are of the opinion that the &quot;filter-killer-wall&quot; combo is the way to go. The first dilemma tries to filter out personnel essential to passing the second, and as a result, the second dilemma will succeed in killing one or more personnel. Then the third dilemma, a wall, will hopefully &quot;stop&quot; the remaining crew/AT. This has seen fairly consistent success, in my experience.<br>
<br>
More recently, the &quot;wall-filter-killer&quot; combo has seen increased tournament usage. The initial wall compels your opponent to commit a significant number of his personnel to pass it (most recently, Ferengi Infestation has been used in this capacity). With lots of personnel to play with, the filter tries, as before, to remove personnel with the skills to pass the third dilemma. Then, with the mega-crew filtered down, the killer strikes, eliminating a large number of the remaining personnel, with any luck. This has seen less consistent success, but the results of a successful wall-filter-killer are usually far greater than filter-killer-wall.<br>
<br>
The choice is ultimately up to the deck-builder; would you rather have dilemmas that the opponent may not go into with his strongest personnel, and be stymied for awhile? Or would you rather your opponent commit a large number of personnel (meaning more skills to choose from), that you pick off two or three at a time?<br>
<br>
I leave the choice to you. In the next installment, Dilemma Combos 103, I will begin suggesting specific combos and how to improve them. Until then, happy combo-ing. </span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=9"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=9"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="/stccg/global/images/back.gif" border="0" ></a></TD><TD><a href="articleprint.php3?article=9" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="/stccg/global/images/print.gif" border="0"></a></TD></TR></TABLE>
